
Your "To-Do List": Benchmarks & Metrics
To do this correctly, you need to run three specific tools. Here is your cheat sheet:

Tool 1: stress-ng (The Scaling Test)
What to look for: Bogo Ops/s.

The Goal: Run it with 1 core, then 2, then 4, then 8.

The "Correct" way: If you double the cores, the Bogo Ops should almost exactly double. If the laptop (x86) doesn't double, you've found the Tipping Point.

Tool 2: fio (The Memory Wall Test)
What to look for: Bandwidth (MB/s) and Latency (µs).

The Goal: Run a "Random Read" test.

The "Correct" way: Increase the "Block Size" (from 4k to 1M). Watch for the point where the speed (MB/s) stops going up—that is the Memory Wall.

Tool 3: STREAM (The Industry Gold Standard)
What to look for: Triad (MB/s).

The Goal: This is the benchmark everyone in those articles uses. It measures the absolute max speed of the RAM.

The "Correct" way: Compile and run it. If your Power10 VM shows 50,000 MB/s and your laptop shows 15,000 MB/s, you have proven the "Enterprise Scaling" pillar.